OVERVIEW
		RECIPE_0 - red lentil curry
		RECIPE_1 - leek and cheese soup
		RECIPE_2 - instant thai curry noodle soup
		RECIPE_3 - thai red curry
		RECIPE_4 - vegan butter "chicken" with baked tofu



RECIPE_0

	NAME
			red lentil curry

	SYNOPSIS
			red lentil curry [side options]
			red lentil curry with freshly toasted/roasted naan or pita
			red lentil curry with basmati rice

	INGREDIENTS
			for 2 servings:
				Red lentils                 [200g]
				Vegetable stock             [500ml, more as needed]
				Crushed tomatoes            [250ml]
				Fresh tomatoes cubed        [2pcs]
				Pre-cooked chickpeas        [300g]
				Full-fat coconut milk       [400ml]
				Fresh turmeric              [2-3cm long piece]
				Fresh ginger                [2-3cm long piece]
				Fresh garlic                [2-3 cloves]
				Fresh green pepper (hot)    [1 or 2 peppers]
				Red onion                   [1, medium size]
				Cumin powder                [2 tsp]
				Coriander powder            [2 tsp]
				Chili powder                [2 tsp]
				Paprika powder (sweet)      [1 tsp]
				Curry powder                [2 tsp]
				Lemon juice                 [half a lemon]
				Salt
				Pepper

	DIRECTIONS
			0   Mince or grate onions, garlic, ginger, green peppers and
				turmeric; rinse red lentils thoroughly

			1   Roast onions, garlic, ginger, green peppers and turmeric
				over medium heat until browned and fragrant

			2   Add powder spices, roast until fragrant. watch for burning

			3   Glaze with vegetable stock, add rinsed red lentils,
				crushed and cubed tomatoes

			4   Simmer for 20 to 25min, adding more vegetable stock as
				needed for lentils to become al dente

			5   After 15min, add full-fat coconut milk

			6   Once red lentils are almost al dente, add pre-cooked
				chickpeas

			7   Season to taste with salt and pepper

			8   Add juice of half a lemon

	SERVING
			Serve with freshly cooked basmati rice or toasted/freshly
			baked pita or naan


RECIPE_1

	NAME
			leek and cheese soup

	INGREDIENTS
			for 4 servings:
				Leek                        [2 stalks]
				Red onion                   [2 medium]
				Garlic                      [4 cloves]
				Creme fraiche               [250ml]
				Vegetable broth             [700ml]
				Soft cheese                 [150g]
				Soy minced meat             [200g]
				Vegetable oil
				Salt
				Pepper

	DIRECTIONS
			0   Wash and cut leek into small (~1cm width) rings. Dice red
				onion, mince garlic

			1   Into a large pot, pour vegetable oil and fry chopped onion
				and the soy meat until crispy and brown. Add garlic,
				careful not to burn it.

			2   Throw sliced leek into the pot and stir. Deglaze with
				vegetable broth after a minute or two. Let simmer for
				about ten minutes

			3   Add generous amount of grated soft cheese as well as the
				creme fraiche. Mix thoroughly. Season to taste with salt
				and pepper.

	SERVING
			Serve with fresh baguette.


RECIPE_2

	NAME
			instant thai curry noodle soup

	INGREDIENTS
			for 2 servings:
				Coconut milk                [120ml]
				Thai green curry paste      [2Tbsp]
				Garlic, crushed             [2 clove]
				Firm tofu, drained, cubed   [200g]
				Red cabbage, shredded       [as desired]
				Carrot, grated/julienned    [1 pc, medium]
				Red bell pepper, sliced     [1 pc]
				Vegetable bouillon          [20g]
				Fresh spinach, chopped      [30g]
				White rice noodles          [120g]


	DIRECTIONS
			0   In a bowl, combine the coconut cream, Thai curry paste, and garlic.

			1   Add the tofu and toss to coat.

			2   If making a to-go meal, transfer the tofu to a mason jar
				or large heat-safe airtight container. If enjoying it
				right away, leave it in the bowl.

			3   Layer the cabbage, carrot, and bell pepper over the tofu, and
				crumble the bouillon cube overtop. Then add the spinach and rice
				noodles.

			4   Store until ready to eat

			5   When ready to eat, add 1L boiling water so that all the
				ingredients are fully submerged, and stir. Cover and let sit for 5
				minutes to soften the noodles. If after this time the noodles are
				not softened enough to your liking, it could be that the veggies
				were cold or the water was not hot enough. In this case, consider
				microwaving or heating on the stove for 1 - 2 minutes.


	SERVING
			Garnish with desired toppings and a squeeze of fresh lime.


RECIPE_3

	NAME
			thai red curry

	INGREDIENTS
			for 4 servings:
				Red onions                  [2 pc, medium]
				Potatoes, diced             [2 pc, medium]
				Garlic, crushed             [2 cloves]
				Thai red curry paste        [3 Tbsp]
				Basmati rice                [200g]
				Tofu strips, seasoned       [350g]
				Red bell peppers, chopped   [2 pc]
				Broccoli, chopped           [1 pc]
				Full-fat coconut milk       [400ml]
				Soy sauce                   [1 Tbsp]
				Roasted cashews, chopped    [handful]
				Coconut yogurt, optional    [1 Tbsp]

	DIRECTIONS
			0   In a large pot on high heat, add the oil and sauté the shallots
				for about 5 minutes, or until lightly golden. Add splashes of water
				as needed to de-glaze the pan.

			1   Add the garlic and cook for another 2 minutes.

			2   Add the potatoes and curry paste, cook for 1-2 minutes.

			3   Then add the water to the pot. Bring to a boil, then reduce to
				a simmer, and cover with a lid. Simmer for 15 minutes.

			4   Meanwhile, cook the rice according to package instructions.

			5   Add the remaining ingredients to the pot and cook for about 6 -
				8 minutes, or until the veggies are cooked to desired tenderness.

	SERVING
			Serve with rice, top with cashews and coconut yogurt.



RECIPE_4

	NAME
			vegan butter "chicken" with baked tofu

	INGREDIENTS
			for 4 servings:
				TOFU:
				Firm tofu, cubed            [450g]
				Soy yogurt                  [120ml]
				Garam masala                [2 tsp]
				Cumin                       [1 tsp]
				Coriander                   [1 tsp]
				Turmeric                    [1 tsp]
				Salt

				SAUCE:
				Cashews                     [30g]
				Garlic, minced              [5 cloves]
				Onion, chopped              [1 pc, large]
				Jalapeno, seedless, minced  [1 pc]
				Ginger, grated              [2 tsp]
				Garam masala                [1.5 Tbsp]
				Coriander                   [1.5 Tbsp]
				Cumin                       [1.5 Tbsp]
				Cayenne pepper              [0.25 tsp]
				Canned crushed tomatoes     [400g]
				Tomato paste                [2 Tbsp]
				Agave Syrup                 [0.5 Tbsp]
				Full-fat coconut milk       [400ml]
				Salt

	DIRECTIONS
			0   Soak the raw cashews in boiling water to soften. Set aside for
				10 minutes. Preheat the oven to 200°C.

			1   In a bowl, combine the tofu, yogurt, garam masala, cumin,
				coriander, turmeric, and salt.

			2   Transfer the tofu onto a lined baking tray and bake for 15 - 20
				minutes, stirring once or twice. Keep an eye on it to prevent
				burning.

			3   To a large pot on medium-high heat, sauté the oil, garlic,
				onion, jalapeño, and ginger for 5 minutes. Add splashes of water as
				needed to deglaze the pan.

			4   Add in the garam masala, coriander, cumin, salt, and cayenne
				pepper and cook for 1 more minute, stirring throughout to toast the
				spices.

			5   Then add the drained cashews, diced tomatoes, tomato paste,
				agave syrup, and coconut milk. Blend everything using an immersion
				blender or transfer to a standing blender to blend until smooth.
				Let simmer on low, and cover with a lid.

			6   Once the tofu is golden, remove it from the oven and add it to
				the pot. Give it a gentle stir and serve.

	SERVING
			Serve with basmati rice or freshly baked naan.



